### 9. The Potentiality Fork

**Source:** Atlas — Nature of Time, Strategy 002, Explorations 003-004

**The result:** The single genuine difference between the computational and process interpretations of time is the ontological status of unactualized possibilities:
- Computational view: unactualized possibilities never had ontological status — they're computational paths not taken (epistemic)
- Process view: unactualized possibilities were real potentia (Heisenberg's term) that are genuinely extinguished upon actualization (ontological)

This fork has specific consequences: it determines whether the "now" is ontologically special or merely a computational frontier, whether the arrow is intrinsic or requires the Past Hypothesis, and it maps directly onto real interpretive divides in quantum mechanics (collapse vs. many-worlds vs. hidden variables). Not a verbal difference — it constrains which physical theories are acceptable.

**More info:** `current_hunts/atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-002/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md`, `current_hunts/atlas/execution/instances/nature-of-time/strategies/strategy-002/FINAL-REPORT.md`

